<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Dishwasher not draining</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Standing water at the bottom of the tub. Three places it almost always lives.</h2>

    <p>Standing water after a dishwasher cycle traces to one of three places about 85% of the time: the filter at the bottom of the tub, the drain pump itself, or the drain hose between the dishwasher and the kitchen plumbing. The other 15% splits between the air gap on top of the sink, a garbage disposal knockout plug that was never removed at install, and (rarely) the control board misreading the cycle state.</p>

    <p>SoCal's hard water is the variable that changes the math. LADWP, MWD, Calleguas, Santa Margarita, and Rancho California municipal water averages 12 to 18 grains per gallon hardness, harder than most US cities. Calcium and magnesium accumulate on the filter, inside the drain pump impeller housing, and on the lower spray arm hub faster than in soft-water markets. That is why filter cleaning resolves a meaningful share of LA-area no-drain calls without any parts replacement.</p>

    <p>We service drain failures across LA County, Orange County, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. <strong>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> Same-day across the central counties. BHGS #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). 90-day warranty on parts and labor.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TOP 5 CAUSES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Top 5 causes of standing water</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">In honest frequency order.</h2>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>1. Filter clog (40 to 50% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The cylindrical filter at the bottom of the tub catches food debris, glass shards, label fragments, and (in SoCal) accumulated mineral buildup. When it clogs, water cannot reach the drain pump intake, so the pump runs dry or stalls. Symptom: standing water plus often a faint humming sound during the drain phase. Fix: pull the filter, rinse under hot water, scrub with a toothbrush, reinstall. Most homeowners can do this; most don't, because nobody told them.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Visual inspection. Filter caked with food and mineral residue is unambiguous.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Filter clean is often $89 diagnostic only, no parts charged. We don't bill for parts when there are no parts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>2. Drain pump failure (20 to 25% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The drain pump is the small motorized impeller that pushes wash water up through the drain hose to the sink plumbing. Year 6 to 9 typical service life on LA-area dishwashers (faster than soft-water markets due to mineral abrasion on the impeller). When the pump motor fails or the impeller seizes, water stays in the tub regardless of filter condition.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Listen during the drain phase. Functioning pump produces a steady whirring sound for 30 to 90 seconds. Silence equals motor failure. Loud grinding equals impeller jammed (often by a fruit pit, broken glass, or label adhesive).</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Drain pump replacement $260 to $440 typical, including labor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>3. Drain hose kink, clog, or high-loop failure (15% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The drain hose runs from the dishwasher under the cabinet to the sink drain or garbage disposal. Two failure modes: kink (cabinet movement, dishwasher pulled out for prior service) or interior clog (grease buildup over years narrows the hose ID). High-loop is a code requirement (the hose must rise to under-counter height before dropping to the disposal) that prevents drain water from siphoning back. Failed high-loop causes intermittent backflow.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Pull the dishwasher forward, visually inspect the hose run, check the high loop is intact, blow air through to confirm no clog.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Hose replacement $180 to $280, sometimes just re-routing if the kink is the only issue ($89 diagnostic, no parts).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>4. Air gap clog (10% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The chrome cap on top of your sink (next to the faucet) is the air gap. Required by California plumbing code on most installations. Drain water from the dishwasher runs up through the air gap before going down to the disposal or sink drain. Debris accumulates in the air gap chamber over years and blocks flow.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Pop the chrome cap, look inside the chamber for debris.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Clean the chamber. $120 to $180 if part of a service visit; usually combined with filter and hose check.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>5. Garbage disposal knockout plug not removed (rare but specific)</h3>
      <p>New garbage disposals ship with a knockout plug in the dishwasher inlet stub. Installer is supposed to remove the plug before connecting the dishwasher drain hose. If the plug is left in place, the dishwasher cannot drain into the disposal at all. Symptom: dishwasher worked fine until garbage disposal install last week, now it doesn't drain at all.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Disconnect dishwasher hose at the disposal, look up at the inlet, see the white plastic plug still in place.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Knockout the plug, reconnect the hose. $89 diagnostic only, no parts. We see this 4 to 6 times per month following recent disposal install. The fix is fast; the cause is installer error not appliance failure, and we tell you straight.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 DIAGNOSTIC WALKTHROUGH -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · How we diagnose</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Six-step protocol. 15 to 25 minutes from arrival.</h2>

    <ol class="diag-list">
      <li><strong>Filter inspection.</strong> Pull the filter, photograph the buildup, note food vs mineral content. Often diagnostic ends here.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pump audio test.</strong> Run a drain cycle, listen for pump activity. Silent = motor failure. Grinding = impeller jam. Whirring without water movement = impeller worn.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain hose check.</strong> Pull the unit forward, visually inspect the hose run, verify the high loop is intact, check for kinks at cabinet edge.</li>
      <li><strong>Air gap chamber inspection.</strong> Pop the chrome cap on the sink top, look for debris.</li>
      <li><strong>Disposal connection check.</strong> If recent disposal install, verify knockout plug was removed.</li>
      <li><strong>Control board codes if equipped.</strong> Modern dishwashers (Bosch, Miele, Samsung, LG, KitchenAid 2014+) display drain-related error codes (Bosch E22 / E24, Samsung 5C / 5E, LG OE, Whirlpool/KitchenAid F9E1). Codes confirm or contradict the visual findings.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Total diagnostic time 15 to 25 minutes. We give you a written quote before any repair. <strong>$89 residential diagnostic, waived if you proceed with repair.</strong></p>
  </div>
</section>

